{
  "What type of cells does mitosis produce, and how many?": "",
  "Four genetically different haploid cells": "",
  "Two cells with half the chromosome number": "",
  "Two genetically identical daughter nuclei, each with the same chromosome number as the parent cell": "",
  "One larger cell with double the DNA": "",
  "Mitosis is an equational division of the nucleus that produces two daughter nuclei genetically identical to the parent. In humans, each daughter cell has 46 chromosomes (2n = 46), the same as the original cell. Mitosis maintains chromosome number and genetic identity during growth and repair.": "",
  "What is the correct order of the four phases of mitosis?": "",
  "Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase (PMAT)": "",
  "Telophase, Prophase, Anaphase, Metaphase": "",
  "Anaphase, Telophase, Prophase, Metaphase": "",
  "Metaphase, Anaphase, Prophase, Telophase": "",
  "The mnemonic PMAT helps remember the order: Prophase (chromosomes condense, spindle forms), Metaphase (chromosomes align at the equator), Anaphase (sister chromatids separate), Telophase (nuclear envelopes reform). Cytokinesis (cytoplasm division) typically overlaps with telophase.": "",
  "What three key events occur during prophase of mitosis?": "",
  "Nuclear envelopes reform, chromosomes decondense, and nucleoli reappear": "",
  "Sister chromatids separate, the cell elongates, and cytokinesis begins": "",
  "DNA replicates, the cell plate forms, and chromosomes align": "",
  "Chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes, the nuclear envelope begins to break down, and spindle fibers start forming from the centrosomes": "",
  "Prophase is the first stage of mitosis. Chromatin fibers coil and condense into compact, visible chromosomes (each consisting of two sister chromatids). The centrosomes migrate to opposite poles and begin assembling the mitotic spindle from microtubules. The nuclear envelope breaks apart (prometaphase), allowing spindle fibers to access the chromosomes.": "",
  "During metaphase, where are the chromosomes positioned in the cell?": "",
  "Scattered randomly throughout the cytoplasm without any specific organizational pattern": "",
  "Clustered at one pole of the cell near the centrosome that organized the spindle fibers": "",
  "Inside the nucleolus, where ribosomal RNA is being synthesized alongside the chromosomes": "",
  "Aligned along the cell's equator (metaphase plate), with kinetochore fibers attached to centromeres from both poles": "",
  "During metaphase, spindle fibers attach to the kinetochores on each chromosome's centromere and align all chromosomes along the metaphase plate (the imaginary equatorial plane of the cell). This precise alignment ensures that when sister chromatids separate in anaphase, each pole receives one copy of every chromosome.": "",
  "What happens during anaphase of mitosis?": "",
  "Chromosomes condense and become visible as the nuclear envelope begins to break down": "",
  "Sister chromatids separate at the centromere and are pulled by shortening spindle fibers to opposite poles of the cell": "",
  "Nuclear envelopes reform around each chromosome set and nucleoli reappear in the daughter nuclei": "",
  "DNA replication occurs as the cell duplicates its entire genome for the upcoming division": "",
  "Anaphase is the shortest and most dramatic phase of mitosis. The enzyme separase cleaves cohesin proteins holding sister chromatids together at the centromere. Motor proteins at the kinetochores walk along shortening microtubules, pulling the now-individual chromosomes to opposite poles. The cell also elongates as non-kinetochore microtubules push the poles apart.": "",
  "What happens during telophase, and what follows it?": "",
  "DNA replicates and the cell prepares for another division by synthesizing additional proteins needed": "",
  "Chromosomes condense and the spindle forms as centrioles migrate to opposite poles of the cell": "",
  "Nuclear envelopes reform around each set of chromosomes, chromosomes decondense back to chromatin, and nucleoli reappear — cytokinesis then divides the cytoplasm into two daughter cells": "",
  "Sister chromatids separate and move to opposite poles, pulled by shortening kinetochore microtubules": "",
  "Telophase is essentially the reverse of prophase. Nuclear envelopes reassemble around each set of chromosomes using membrane fragments from the ER. Chromosomes decondense back into chromatin, nucleoli reappear, and the spindle disassembles. Cytokinesis (cleavage furrow in animals, cell plate in plants) typically overlaps with telophase to complete cell division.": "",
  "What are spindle fibers made of, and what structure organizes them in animal cells?": "",
  "Intermediate filaments organized by the Golgi apparatus": "",
  "Myosin filaments organized by ribosomes": "",
  "Actin filaments organized by the nucleus": "",
  "Microtubules (polymers of tubulin protein) organized by centrosomes containing centrioles": "",
  "Spindle fibers are microtubules assembled from tubulin protein dimers. In animal cells, centrosomes (each containing two centrioles) serve as microtubule-organizing centers (MTOCs) that nucleate and organize spindle fibers. Three types exist: kinetochore microtubules (attach to chromosomes), polar microtubules (overlap at the midzone), and astral microtubules (anchor the spindle to the cell cortex).": "",
  "After mitosis and cytokinesis, how many chromosomes does each human daughter cell contain?": "",
  "The number varies between daughter cells depending on how the chromosomes are randomly distributed": "",
  "46 chromosomes (diploid) — the same number as the parent cell, because mitosis is an equational division": "",
  "92 chromosomes (tetraploid), because the DNA was replicated during S phase without subsequent division": "",
  "23 chromosomes (haploid), because mitosis separates homologous chromosomes into different daughter cells": "",
  "Mitosis maintains the chromosome number. During S phase, each of the 46 chromosomes is replicated to form sister chromatids. In anaphase, sister chromatids separate, ensuring each daughter cell receives exactly 46 chromosomes (2n = 46). This is fundamentally different from meiosis, which reduces the chromosome number to 23 (n = 23).": "",
  "Why is mitosis essential for multicellular organisms?": "",
  "It is used only during embryonic development and plays no role in maintaining adult tissues": "",
  "It enables growth (increasing cell number), tissue repair (replacing damaged cells), and maintenance (replacing worn-out cells like skin and blood cells)": "",
  "It decreases the number of cells in the body through programmed cell death and selective elimination": "",
  "It produces gametes for sexual reproduction, ensuring genetic diversity in the next generation": "",
  "Mitosis is critical throughout an organism's life. During development, it increases cell number from a single zygote to trillions of cells. In adults, it replaces cells that wear out (skin cells every 2-3 weeks, red blood cells every 120 days) and repairs damaged tissues after injury.": "",
  "What can happen if errors occur during mitosis?": "",
  "Errors are always corrected before the cell divides, so daughter cells always receive normal chromosomes": "",
  "Errors can result in daughter cells with abnormal chromosome numbers (aneuploidy), cell death (apoptosis), or uncontrolled cell division (potentially leading to cancer)": "",
  "Errors make cells stronger and more resistant to disease by introducing beneficial genetic variation": "",
  "The cell always functions normally regardless of errors because backup copies of genes compensate": "",
  "Mitotic errors can have serious consequences. Nondisjunction creates aneuploid cells with too many or too few chromosomes. If cell cycle checkpoints fail to catch errors, daughter cells may accumulate mutations that disable growth controls — a key step in cancer development. Cells with severe errors typically undergo apoptosis (programmed cell death).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'mitosis'?": "",
  "The division of a cell's nucleus into two genetically identical daughter nuclei, consisting of prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase (followed by cytokinesis to produce two complete cells)": "",
  "The division of cytoplasm between two daughter cells, completing the process of cellular reproduction": "",
  "The replication of DNA during S phase of interphase, producing two identical copies of each chromosome": "",
  "A type of cell division that produces four haploid gametes through two successive nuclear divisions": "",
  "Mitosis is specifically the division of the nucleus (karyokinesis). It encompasses four sequential phases: prophase (condensation), metaphase (alignment), anaphase (separation), and telophase (nuclear reformation). Cytokinesis, the division of the cytoplasm, is a separate but usually concurrent process. Together, mitosis and cytokinesis produce two genetically identical daughter cells.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'prophase'?": "",
  "The first phase of mitosis during which chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes, the mitotic spindle begins to form from the centrosomes, and the nuclear envelope starts to break down": "",
  "The phase when sister chromatids separate and move to opposite poles of the dividing cell": "",
  "The phase when the cell grows and replicates its DNA in preparation for the upcoming division": "",
  "The phase when chromosomes align at the metaphase plate with kinetochores attached to spindle fibers": "",
  "Prophase marks the beginning of mitosis. Three major events occur: (1) Chromatin condenses into compact chromosomes visible under a light microscope, (2) Centrosomes migrate toward opposite poles and begin nucleating spindle microtubules, and (3) The nuclear envelope fragments into vesicles (prometaphase), allowing spindle fibers to access chromosomes.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'metaphase'?": "",
  "The phase when DNA is being replicated in the nucleus as part of the S phase of interphase": "",
  "The phase when chromosomes first become visible as chromatin condenses during early prophase": "",
  "The phase of mitosis during which all chromosomes are aligned along the cell's equator (metaphase plate), with kinetochore microtubules from both poles attached to each chromosome's centromere": "",
  "The phase when the nuclear envelope reforms and chromosomes decondense back into chromatin": "",
  "Metaphase ensures accurate chromosome distribution. Each chromosome must achieve bi-orientation — with kinetochore fibers from opposite poles attached to the two sister chromatids. The spindle assembly checkpoint verifies that all chromosomes are properly attached and aligned at the metaphase plate before allowing the cell to proceed to anaphase.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'anaphase'?": "",
  "The phase of mitosis during which cohesin proteins are cleaved, sister chromatids separate at the centromere, and shortening spindle fibers pull the individual chromosomes to opposite poles of the cell": "",
  "The phase when chromosomes line up at the equator of the cell along the metaphase plate": "",
  "The phase when chromosomes condense and become visible as distinct structures in the nucleus": "",
  "The phase when cytokinesis is completed and two separate daughter cells are fully formed": "",
  "Anaphase is the shortest and most dramatic phase of mitosis. The anaphase-promoting complex (APC/C) activates separase, which cleaves cohesin proteins holding sister chromatids together. Kinetochore microtubules shorten (depolymerize) at the kinetochore end, pulling chromatids poleward (Anaphase A). Simultaneously, polar microtubules lengthen and push the poles apart (Anaphase B).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'cytokinesis'?": "",
  "The replication of organelles during interphase in preparation for the upcoming cell division": "",
  "The division of the cytoplasm into two separate daughter cells, occurring after mitosis — in animal cells via a cleavage furrow (contractile ring of actin/myosin), and in plant cells via a cell plate (fused Golgi vesicles forming a new cell wall)": "",
  "The division of the nucleus into two daughter nuclei, which is the process known as mitosis": "",
  "The movement of chromosomes to opposite poles during anaphase, driven by shortening spindle fibers": "",
  "Cytokinesis physically separates one cell into two. In animal cells, a contractile ring of actin and myosin filaments assembles beneath the plasma membrane and constricts, forming a cleavage furrow that pinches the cell in two. In plant cells, Golgi-derived vesicles fuse at the cell equator to form a cell plate that develops into a new cell wall separating the daughter cells.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'telophase'?": "",
  "The phase when the cytoplasm divides into two separate cells through cleavage or cell plate formation": "",
  "The phase when the cell first begins to divide as chromosomes condense and the spindle apparatus forms": "",
  "The phase when DNA is being replicated in preparation for division during the synthesis period of interphase": "",
  "The final phase of mitosis during which nuclear envelopes reform around each set of separated chromosomes, chromosomes decondense back into chromatin, nucleoli reappear, and the mitotic spindle disassembles": "",
  "Telophase reverses the events of prophase. Nuclear envelope fragments reassemble around each chromosome set, chromosomes uncoil to resume gene expression, nucleoli (sites of ribosomal RNA synthesis) become visible again, and spindle microtubules depolymerize. By the end of telophase, two distinct nuclei exist within the still-shared cytoplasm.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 'mitotic spindle'?": "",
  "A structure made of microtubules organized by centrosomes that attaches to chromosome kinetochores and is responsible for separating chromosomes to opposite poles during mitosis": "",
  "A protein that holds sister chromatids together at the centromere region until anaphase begins": "",
  "The ring of actin and myosin that forms the cleavage furrow during cytokinesis in animal cells": "",
  "A network of DNA strands connecting chromosomes to the nuclear envelope during interphase": "",
  "The mitotic spindle is an assembly of microtubules that forms during prophase from centrosomes (MTOCs). It consists of three types of microtubules: kinetochore microtubules (attach to chromosomes via kinetochores and pull them), polar/interpolar microtubules (overlap at the midzone and push poles apart), and astral microtubules (anchor the spindle to the cell cortex and help position it).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 'kinetochore'?": "",
  "A membrane structure that forms the cell plate in plant cells during the final stage of cytokinesis": "",
  "The region of DNA that codes for centromere proteins essential for chromosome segregation during division": "",
  "A multi-protein complex that assembles on the centromere of each chromatid and serves as the attachment point for spindle microtubules, enabling chromosome movement during mitosis": "",
  "An enzyme that replicates DNA during S phase by adding complementary nucleotides to the template strand": "",
  "The kinetochore is a complex of over 80 proteins that assembles at the centromeric region of each chromatid. It serves as the interface between the chromosome and spindle microtubules. Motor proteins in the kinetochore (including dynein and CENP-E) generate force for chromosome movement. The spindle assembly checkpoint monitors kinetochore attachment to ensure all chromosomes are properly connected before anaphase.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a 'cell plate'?": "",
  "A rigid structure surrounding all cells that provides structural support and protection from lysis": "",
  "The cleavage furrow formed in animal cells during cytokinesis by an actin-myosin contractile ring": "",
  "The metaphase plate where chromosomes align during the middle phase of mitotic nuclear division": "",
  "A structure unique to plant cell cytokinesis, formed when Golgi-derived vesicles carrying cell wall materials fuse at the center of the dividing cell to create a new cell wall and membrane between the two daughter cells": "",
  "The cell plate forms in plant cells because their rigid cell wall prevents the membrane pinching that occurs in animal cells. During telophase, vesicles from the Golgi apparatus (carrying polysaccharides and glycoproteins for wall construction) are guided by remaining phragmoplast microtubules to the cell's equator, where they fuse to form the cell plate. This grows outward until it fuses with the existing cell wall, completely separating the daughter cells.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 'cleavage furrow'?": "",
  "The space between two adjacent cells in a tissue, filled with extracellular matrix components": "",
  "A groove on a chromosome where the centromere is located and kinetochore proteins assemble": "",
  "An indentation on the surface of an animal cell formed by a contractile ring of actin and myosin filaments that constricts progressively during cytokinesis, pinching the cell in two": "",
  "A structure that forms in plant cells during cytokinesis from Golgi-derived vesicles fusing together": "",
  "The cleavage furrow is the mechanism of cytokinesis in animal cells. A contractile ring assembles just beneath the plasma membrane at the cell equator (positioned by signals from the mitotic spindle midzone). The ring is composed of actin filaments and myosin II motor proteins that contract, pulling the membrane inward like a drawstring purse until the cell pinches into two daughter cells.": "",
  "In a biology lab, students examine an onion root tip under a microscope and observe cells in different stages. They count 20 cells in interphase, 10 in prophase, 6 in metaphase, 3 in anaphase, and 5 in telophase. What can they conclude about the relative duration of each phase?": "",
  "The number of cells in each phase is proportional to the time spent in that phase — interphase is longest (~45%), prophase is the longest mitotic phase (~23%), and anaphase is the shortest (~7%)": "",
  "Anaphase is the longest phase because most cells were observed in anaphase during the microscopy count": "",
  "The counts are random and reveal nothing about timing because cells divide unpredictably in the root tip": "",
  "All phases of mitosis take equal time, so each phase should have the same number of observed cells": "",
  "This is a classic mitotic index experiment. In a rapidly dividing tissue like the onion root tip meristem, the proportion of cells observed in each phase reflects the duration of that phase (assuming cells are asynchronous). More cells in interphase means it takes the longest. Among mitotic phases, prophase has the most cells (longest mitotic phase), and anaphase has the fewest (shortest phase, ~3–5 minutes).": "",
  "A patient's tumor biopsy shows cells with 92 chromosomes instead of the normal 46. The spindle assembly checkpoint (SAC) appears to be non-functional in these cells. How does a defective SAC contribute to this abnormality?": "",
  "The SAC normally delays anaphase until all kinetochores are properly attached to spindle fibers from both poles — without it, cells enter anaphase with misattached chromosomes, causing nondisjunction and progressive chromosome accumulation (92 = near-tetraploid)": "",
  "SAC dysfunction only affects meiosis, not mitosis, because the checkpoint proteins differ between divisions": "",
  "The SAC normally prevents DNA replication, so without it DNA is copied too many times during S phase": "",
  "The SAC causes chromosomes to replicate additional copies, leading to extra chromosomes in daughter cells": "",
  "The spindle assembly checkpoint (SAC) is a surveillance mechanism that monitors kinetochore-microtubule attachment during prometaphase/metaphase. Unattached kinetochores generate a 'wait' signal (Mad2-Cdc20 complex) that inhibits the anaphase-promoting complex (APC/C). Without a functional SAC, cells proceed to anaphase despite misattached or unattached chromosomes, resulting in unequal chromosome distribution. Over many divisions, this leads to massive aneuploidy — the 92-chromosome count suggests failed cytokinesis or repeated nondisjunction events.": "",
  "A pharmacologist is comparing two anti-cancer drugs: Taxol (paclitaxel) and colchicine. Both target microtubules but through opposite mechanisms. How do their mechanisms differ, and why do both ultimately block cell division?": "",
  "Colchicine prevents microtubule assembly (blocks polymerization) while Taxol prevents microtubule disassembly (stabilizes polymers) — both disrupt the dynamic instability required for spindle function, arresting cells in mitosis": "",
  "Both drugs destroy microtubules by breaking them into small fragments that cannot function in cell division": "",
  "Taxol prevents DNA replication while colchicine prevents cytokinesis by blocking cleavage furrow formation": "",
  "Neither drug affects microtubules; they both target the cell membrane and disrupt nutrient transport": "",
  "Microtubule dynamic instability (constant assembly and disassembly) is essential for spindle function. Colchicine binds free tubulin dimers, preventing polymerization — no new microtubules can form. Taxol binds assembled microtubules and prevents depolymerization — existing microtubules become rigid. Both disrupt the dynamic behavior needed for chromosome capture, alignment, and segregation. The SAC detects the resulting attachment errors and arrests cells in mitosis, ultimately triggering apoptosis.": "",
  "A student views a cell under a microscope and sees that all chromosomes are lined up in a single row at the center of the cell with spindle fibers attached. She wants to identify which phase of mitosis this cell is in. What phase should she identify, and what key evidence supports this?": "",
  "Prophase — the chromosomes are visible and the spindle is forming": "",
  "Anaphase — the chromosomes are being pulled apart": "",
  "Metaphase — all chromosomes are aligned at the metaphase plate (cell equator) with kinetochore fibers attached from both poles, confirming bi-orientation": "",
  "Telophase — the chromosomes are at the center before the nucleus reforms": "",
  "Metaphase is identified by the characteristic alignment of all chromosomes at the metaphase plate (equatorial plane). The key diagnostic features are: (1) chromosomes are maximally condensed and visible, (2) they form a single row at the cell center, and (3) kinetochore microtubules from both poles are attached to each chromosome's centromere (bi-orientation). This alignment is verified by the spindle assembly checkpoint before the cell proceeds to anaphase.": "",
  "Researchers use fluorescently labeled tubulin to study spindle dynamics in living cells. They observe that fluorescence at the kinetochore end of microtubules disappears while new fluorescent subunits are added at the centrosome end. What does this 'Pacman-kinetochore' model tell us about how chromosomes move during anaphase?": "",
  "Kinetochores actively depolymerize microtubules at the attachment point — the kinetochore 'eats' the microtubule like Pac-Man, pulling the chromosome poleward as the fiber shortens from the kinetochore end": "",
  "Chromosomes diffuse randomly to the poles after the spindle disassembles": "",
  "Chromosomes are pushed away from the metaphase plate by growing microtubules": "",
  "Motor proteins on the cell membrane pull the chromosomes to the poles": "",
  "The Pacman-kinetochore model (from fluorescence studies) shows that microtubules depolymerize primarily at the kinetochore end during anaphase A. The kinetochore complex includes depolymerizing motors (like MCAK/Kif2b) and coupling proteins (Ndc80 complex, Dam1 ring in yeast) that maintain attachment to the shortening microtubule tip. Simultaneously, flux-based mechanisms add tubulin at the centrosome end. Combined with dynein motors, this generates the force that moves chromosomes poleward at ~1-2 micrometers per minute.": "",
  "A patient with mosaic Down syndrome has some cells with 47 chromosomes (trisomy 21) and other cells with the normal 46. Unlike typical Down syndrome (caused by meiotic nondisjunction), what type of error during early embryonic development could produce this mosaic pattern?": "",
  "Deletion of chromosome 21 in some cells during early embryonic development reduced the total count": "",
  "Crossing over during all meiotic divisions shuffled chromosome 21 material unevenly between gametes": "",
  "The patient inherited different chromosome numbers from each parent due to errors in gamete formation": "",
  "Mitotic nondisjunction in one cell during early embryonic divisions — one daughter cell gets 3 copies of chromosome 21, the other gets 1 copy, while all other cell lineages from normal divisions retain 46 chromosomes": "",
  "Mosaic Down syndrome occurs when mitotic nondisjunction happens in one cell during early embryonic development after the zygote has already begun dividing. Instead of the meiotic error that causes classic trisomy 21 (present in ALL cells), one mitotic division fails to separate the sister chromatids of chromosome 21. One daughter cell lineage becomes trisomic (47 chromosomes) while cells from unaffected divisions remain normal (46). The severity of symptoms depends on when the error occurs — earlier errors produce more trisomic cells.": "",
  "A cancer research team tests a CDK1 inhibitor drug on rapidly dividing tumor cells. After 48 hours, they find that most treated cells are arrested with condensed chromosomes but have NOT begun separating sister chromatids. At what transition point has the drug blocked the cell cycle, and why?": "",
  "Cytokinesis -- the cells cannot complete division because CDK1 is required for cleavage furrow formation": "",
  "The G₂/M transition — CDK1 (also called Cdc2/CDK1 or MPF) is essential for triggering entry into mitosis; its inhibition arrests cells at the boundary between G₂ and M phase with condensed chromosomes but without progression to anaphase": "",
  "Metaphase/anaphase transition -- the cells are stuck at the spindle checkpoint waiting for proper attachment": "",
  "G1/S checkpoint -- the cells have not replicated their DNA because CDK1 controls S phase entry": "",
  "CDK1 (cyclin-dependent kinase 1), when bound to Cyclin B, forms the MPF (maturation-promoting factor) complex that is the master regulator of mitotic entry. CDK1 phosphorylates dozens of substrates needed for chromosome condensation, nuclear envelope breakdown, and spindle assembly. When CDK1 is inhibited, cells can still begin chromosome condensation (initiated by other kinases like Aurora B) but cannot fully commit to mitotic progression. The arrested cells accumulate at the G₂/M boundary, making CDK1 inhibitors (like RO-3306) important research tools and potential cancer therapeutics.": "",
  "Mature red blood cells (erythrocytes) in humans cannot divide or repair themselves and have a lifespan of about 120 days. A patient with severe anemia receives erythropoietin (EPO) to stimulate red blood cell production. Where are new red blood cells produced, and why can't existing ones just divide by mitosis?": "",
  "Existing red blood cells divide slowly; EPO just speeds up their mitosis to increase production rate": "",
  "Red blood cells are produced in the liver and released into the blood as they mature into erythrocytes": "",
  "New RBCs are produced from hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow — mature erythrocytes cannot undergo mitosis because they lose their nucleus (and all DNA) during differentiation, making cell division impossible": "",
  "White blood cells transform into red blood cells when EPO signals them to change their cell lineage": "",
  "Mature mammalian red blood cells are among the few cell types that CANNOT undergo mitosis because they are enucleated — they expel their nucleus during erythropoiesis to maximize space for hemoglobin. Without a nucleus (no DNA), they cannot replicate chromosomes or divide. New RBCs must be continuously produced from hematopoietic stem cells in the red bone marrow. EPO (a glycoprotein hormone produced mainly by the kidneys) stimulates the proliferation and differentiation of erythroid progenitor cells in the marrow, increasing red blood cell production by 5-8 fold.": "",
  "In a biology lab, students prepare slides from an onion root tip and count cells in each phase of mitosis. Out of 200 cells observed, 120 are in interphase, 40 in prophase, 20 in metaphase, 10 in anaphase, and 10 in telophase. Students then examine a slide from a fast-growing tumor and find that 100 of 200 cells are actively in mitotic phases. What does the comparison of mitotic index (percentage of cells in mitosis) tell us?": "",
  "Both tissues divide at the same rate because they have the same number of cells in their respective samples": "",
  "The root tip is cancerous because so many cells are dividing, indicating uncontrolled cell proliferation": "",
  "Mitotic index has no relationship to cell division rate and is instead a measure of cell size variation": "",
  "The tumor has a mitotic index of 50% versus 40% in the root tip, indicating the tumor tissue has a higher proportion of actively dividing cells — consistent with the uncontrolled cell division characteristic of cancer": "",
  "The mitotic index is calculated as (cells in mitosis / total cells counted) × 100%. For the onion root tip: 80 mitotic cells / 200 = 40%. For the tumor: 100 / 200 = 50%. A higher mitotic index indicates a greater proportion of cells are actively dividing. Pathologists use the mitotic index as a diagnostic tool — a high mitotic index in a tissue biopsy can indicate cancer or other conditions with abnormal cell proliferation. Normal tissues like root tips have high mitotic indices because they are regions of active growth (meristems).": "",
  "Frog embryos undergo extremely rapid cleavage divisions after fertilization, with the first 12 divisions occurring in about 8 hours without any cell growth between divisions. Each successive cell (blastomere) gets smaller. Why can these early embryonic cells skip the G₁ and G₂ growth phases that most somatic cells require?": "",
  "Frog embryonic cells do not need DNA; they divide without replicating chromosomes during early cleavage": "",
  "The cells do grow between divisions, but they grow so fast it appears they skip the growth phases entirely": "",
  "External growth factors from the environment accelerate the divisions beyond the normal rate of mitosis": "",
  "The large egg cell provides a massive stockpile of maternal mRNAs, proteins (including pre-made cyclins and CDKs), ribosomes, and nutrients — so early blastomeres can cycle rapidly through S phase and M phase without needing time to grow or synthesize new organelles": "",
  "Early embryonic cleavage divisions in frogs (Xenopus) are among the fastest cell cycles known (~30 minutes each). The enormous egg (~1.2 mm diameter) is pre-loaded with vast stores of maternal mRNAs, proteins, cyclins, histones, ribosomes, and yolk nutrients during oogenesis. These stockpiled resources allow the embryo to simply alternate between S phase (DNA replication) and M phase (mitosis) without G₁ or G₂ gaps. The result is rapid subdivision of the large egg into thousands of progressively smaller blastomeres, forming a hollow blastula. After about 12 divisions (~4,096 cells), the mid-blastula transition (MBT) activates the embryo's own genome, and normal G₁/G₂ phases resume.": ""
}